Introduction

My datasets are related to Pokemons, which are creatures in the popular gaming and television franchise “Pokemon”. Pokemons have different strengths and unique characteristics to battle against each other. I grew up playing Pokemon, and it’s a source of nostalgia and entertainment for me. I wanted to choose a dataset that was fun and interesting to me so that it would feel less like a school assignment. The variables in my datasets are related to the physical characteristics and background of each Pokemon creature. I found these datasets on Kaggle where the data was pulled from official databases posted by the Pokemon franchise. I think that certain types of Pokemons, such as Fire types, will have higher strength stats than other types, such as Grass types.

# read your datasets in here, e.g., with read_csv()

pokemon1 <- pokemon %>% select(name, attack, defense, type1)

I did an inner join on the two datasets. In pokemon1, there were 801 observations and 4 ID columns, with a total of 1046 unique IDs throughout the whole dataset. In pokemon2, there were 800 observations and 3 ID columns with a total of 900 unique IDS in the whole dataset. After the join, 96 observations in pokemon1 and 97 observations in pokemon2 were dropped after doing the join. There were 97 observations in pokemon1 that were not in pokemon2, but both datasets shared 704 observations. I did the inner join because it dropped unmatched rows in either dataset without a match and keeps the number of rows equal to the intersection of IDs. The two datasets had overlapping data for the observations, so I wanted to keep only the data for the matching observations in each dataset. A potential problem for the dropped observations is that it leaves out data, which could skew future calculations or plots. #

I used all six core ‘dplyr’ functions either in combination or separately to manipulate and explore my dataset. For the mutation, the new variable that I created was named “offense” as it calculates the difference between attack and defense strength. The higher the number, the more powerful offense that the Pokemon had. Negative values indicate a weaker attack and stronger defense. I also just used the other core functions to mess around with my data by reorganizing, renaming, or selecting different things.

Visualizing

ggplot(totalpokemon, aes(x = type1, y = HP), fill = type1) + 
    theme_dark() + geom_bar(stat = "summary", fun = mean, aes(fill = type1)) + 
    geom_errorbar(stat = "summary", fun.data = mean_se) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, 
    hjust = 1), legend.position = "none") + scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 
    80, 10), labels = c("0", "10", "20", "30", "40", "50", "60", 
    "70", "80")) + labs(x = "Pokemon Type", title = "Average HP of each Pokemon Type")

Pokemons are categorized into different Pokemon Types, and HP stands for Hit Points. HP is related to how much damage a Pokemon can sustain before fainting. In plot 1, I displayed the average HP by Pokemon type. I also included standard error bars for each type of Pokemon. There doesn’t appear to be one Pokemon Type that is dominating in HP over the other types. The averages and standard errors of HP across many types appear to be similar and indistinguishable.It does seem to appear that the bug type has the lowest average HP among the types, and the flying type experiences the most varied HP values. There doesn’t appear to be a strong relationship between Pokemon type and HP, but there could be possible correlation.

ggplot(totalpokemon, aes(attack, defense)) + geom_point(size = 2, 
    aes(color = HP)) + theme_dark() + scale_color_gradient2(low = "purple", 
    mid = "white", high = "red", midpoint = 100) + labs(title = "Plotting the Attack, Defense, and HP of All Pokemons") + 
    geom_smooth(method = "lm")

In addition to HP, attack and defense are also statistics related to a Pokemon’s strength. A high attack score relates to high attack power, and the same principle applies to defense. In plot 2, I plotted attack, defense, and HP values for all Pokemon to see if there was a correlation between these variables. Although there appears to be a positive relationship between defense and attack values as shown by the line of best fit, there doesn’t appear to be a correlation to HP scores. The color of the points on the graph indicate the HP value for that Pokemon, and there doesn’t seem to be a trend of HP values across the different defense and attack scores. Although there does appear a more concentrated area of low HP at low attack and defense, there are also high HP values scattered among this area as well, which adds doubt.

ggplot(totalpokemon, aes(x = type1, y = attack)) + geom_boxplot() + 
    geom_jitter(size = 1, alpha = 0.6, aes(color = type1)) + 
    theme_minimal() + labs(x = "Pokemon Type", title = "Type of Pokemon vs. Attack Boxplot") + 
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1), 
        legend.position = "none")

In plot 2, I showed the box plot and distribution of attack values by Pokemon type. This helped display whether Pokemon type had any relation to attack strength. The Pokemon types that had more individual Pokemons experienced a wider range of attack values. From this plot, it appears that the flying type Pokemons have the lowest average attack strength and range. Dragon Pokemon types appear to have the highest attack strengths and lightning types are close behind. There does appear to be some correlation betweeen Pokemon type and attack strength, but this assumption could be unreliable due to differences in the amount of Pokemons in each type.
